@Frassle so this is the interesting case. I can hit this case at runtime when I modify the meta-provider to hard-return an UNKNOWN instead of returning an AWS Provider. 

Like this:

```go
func CallConfigureAwsMethod(ctx *pulumi.Context, inputs provider.CallArgs) (*provider.CallResult, error) {
	if ctx.DryRun() {
		// Really return unknown.
		result := &ConfigureAwsMethodResult{
			AwsProvider: pulumi.UnsafeUnknownOutput(nil).ApplyT(func(x any) *aws.Provider {
				panic("This should not be called")
			}).(aws.ProviderOutput),
		}
		return provider.NewCallResult(result)
	}
```

Note in this case the meta-provider didn't even allocate the AWS provider so there's no URN in the system.

IN this case, we must have an error here. If we do not inject an error, we get an obscure error down the line.

```
    TypeError: provider.getPackage is not a function
        at convertToProvidersMap (/Users/anton.tayanovskyy/code/pulumi-12709/pulumi/sdk/nodejs/resource.ts:517:25)
        at new Resource (/Users/anton.tayanovskyy/code/pulumi-12709/pulumi/sdk/nodejs/resource.ts:439:16)
        at new CustomResource (/Users/anton.tayanovskyy/code/pulumi-12709/pulumi/sdk/nodejs/resource.ts:880:9)
        at new Bucket (/Users/anton.tayanovskyy/code/pulumi-12709/examples/ts-example/node_modules/@pulumi/s3/bucket.ts:522:9)
        at file:///Users/anton.tayanovskyy/code/pulumi-12709/examples/ts-example/index.ts:22:16
        at processTicksAndRejections (node:internal/process/task_queues:95:5)
```

If we want to detect and error out, there's two approaches. One is to detect in every language SDK like this code is written. Another is to perhaps modify github.com/pulumi/pulumi/pkg/v3/resource/provider package to be more schema aware and blame the user code in the Go layer for violating an invariant.. That sounds like a potentially better way to enforce, one place to edit instead of per language.

I do think it should be an error for something that wants to return a "plain" resource to return an unknown without even a URN - this is very different from returning a resource with unknown outputs. No recovery is possible. Having the signature return Promise<T> means this must be an error if it happens.

