I like this pattern better than `init()` `setup()`. It was introduced in dataclasses as well. It's useful for when you need this base class to get constructed by it's sub-classes but there are parts of the construction that depends on the parameters that user has specify first. 

```
class Base:
     def __init__():
            self.initialize_me()
     
     def initialize_me():
            raise NotImplementedError

# this will break because super() has to be called only after self.foo is defined. 
# so the user has to know this. 
# if initialize_me() is called in the `__post_init__()` 
# method user has more flexibility on where to call `super().__init__()`
class A(Base):
     def __init__():
           super().__init__()
           self.foo = "foo"
      
       def initialize_me():
          if self.foo == "foo":
                  self.bar = "zoo"
          else:
                  self.bar = "goo"
```

